# DevOps AI Agent — Beginner's Complete Setup Guide

> This guide answers every question about setting up this project from scratch.
> No prior AWS experience assumed.

---

## 🧱 Part 1: Understanding the Architecture First

Before touching AWS, understand **what each piece is**:

```
Your Local Machine / Lambda
        │
        ▼
[Lambda Function]  ← Your Python code in src/handlers/lambda_handler.py
        │
        ▼
[Bedrock AgentCore]  ← Amazon's AI service — does the thinking
        │
        ▼ (tool calls)
[MCP Servers]  ← Your Python code in src/mcp_servers/
        │
        ├──→ EC2 API       (list/describe/restart instances)
        ├──→ CloudWatch    (get CPU/memory/disk metrics)
        └──→ Teams Webhook (send notifications)
```

**Key insight:** You write the Lambda code locally. AWS runs it in the cloud. The same Python code works both places.

---

## 🤔 Part 2: Why Does Lambda Code Exist Locally?

> **Your question:** "Is this Lambda code defined on AWS manually? Why is there local code for Lambda?"

This confuses everyone at first. Here's the simple truth:

**Lambda is just a Python function that AWS runs for you in the cloud.**

Your file [src/handlers/lambda_handler.py](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/handlers/lambda_handler.py) is just a regular Python file with a [handler()](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/handlers/lambda_handler.py#35-55) function. AWS doesn't know it exists yet. You have to **upload it** to AWS Lambda.

CDK does that upload for you automatically:

```python
# infra/stacks/agent_runner_stack.py — line 30
code=_lambda.Code.from_asset(".")  # ← "take everything in this folder and upload it"
```

So the workflow is:
```
You write Python code locally
         │
         ▼
CDK packages it into a ZIP
         │
         ▼
CDK uploads ZIP to AWS Lambda
         │
         ▼
AWS runs it when CloudWatch alarm fires
```

**You never manually create the Lambda in the Console** — CDK does it.
But you DO need to add env vars manually (or fix the CDK code — shown in Part 6).

---

## 🔐 Part 3: IAM Permissions — What They Are and How to Set Them Up

### What is IAM?

IAM (Identity and Access Management) is AWS's security system.
**Rule:** Every piece of code that touches AWS needs permission to do so.

In this project there are **two identities** that need permissions:

| Who | Needs Permission To |
|---|---|
| **Your local machine** (YOU, running tests) | Call EC2, CloudWatch, Bedrock APIs |
| **Lambda function** (AWS running your code) | Call EC2, CloudWatch, Bedrock APIs |

### 3a. Permissions for YOUR Local Machine

This is done via `~/.aws/credentials`. Run this once:

```bash
aws configure
```

Enter your:
- **Access Key ID** — from AWS Console → IAM → Your user → Security credentials → Create access key
- **Secret Access Key** — shown only once when you create it
- **Region** — `ap-southeast-2`

**Now verify it works:**
```bash
aws sts get-caller-identity
```
You should see your account ID and username. If you get an error, your credentials are wrong.

**What permissions does your IAM user need?**
Go to AWS Console → IAM → Users → your username → Add permissions → Attach policies:

| Policy Name | Why Needed |
|---|---|
| `AmazonEC2ReadOnlyAccess` | For [list_ec2_instances](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/mcp_servers/aws_infra/tools.py#20-76), [describe_ec2_instance](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/mcp_servers/aws_infra/tools.py#78-132) |
| `AmazonEC2FullAccess` | Only if you want to test [restart_ec2_instance](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/mcp_servers/aws_infra/tools.py#134-171) |
| `CloudWatchReadOnlyAccess` | For [get_cpu_metrics](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/mcp_servers/monitoring/tools.py#21-76), [get_disk_usage](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/mcp_servers/monitoring/tools.py#160-223) |
| `AmazonBedrockFullAccess` | For invoking your agent |

**How to add policies:**
1. AWS Console → search "IAM" → Users
2. Click your username
3. Click **"Add permissions"** → **"Attach policies directly"**
4. Search for each policy name above → check the box → **Next** → **Add permissions**

---

### 3b. Permissions for the Lambda Function

When Lambda runs your code in the cloud, it uses an **IAM Role** (not your personal credentials). CDK automatically creates this role and adds these permissions via [infra/stacks/agent_runner_stack.py](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/infra/stacks/agent_runner_stack.py):

```python
# Lines 44–78 in agent_runner_stack.py — CDK adds these automatically
ec2:DescribeInstances    ✅ Already in CDK
ec2:StopInstances        ✅ Already in CDK
ec2:StartInstances       ✅ Already in CDK
cloudwatch:GetMetricStatistics  ✅ Already in CDK
bedrock:InvokeAgent      ✅ Already in CDK
bedrock:InvokeModel      ✅ Already in CDK
```

> [!NOTE]
> **You don't need to manually add any IAM permissions for Lambda** — CDK handles it all when you run `cdk deploy`. The only reason you'd add them manually is if you're NOT using CDK.

**The Bedrock permission should target your specific agent:**
After `cdk deploy`, go to:
```
AWS Console → Lambda → devops-ai-agent-handler → Configuration → Permissions
→ Click the Role name → Add this inline policy:
```
```json
{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Action": ["bedrock:InvokeAgent"],
    "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:bedrock:ap-southeast-2:YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID:agent/KYZ4EKSMX5",
        "arn:aws:bedrock:ap-southeast-2:YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID:agent-alias/KYZ4EKSMX5/LFVTIWMNFK"
    ]
}
```
Replace `YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID` with your 12-digit account ID (visible at top right of AWS Console).

---

## 📊 Part 4: CloudWatch Agent — Memory & Disk Metrics

### Why This Matters

Your code has two tools that need extra setup:
- [get_memory_metrics](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/mcp_servers/monitoring/tools.py#101-158) → needs `CWAgent` namespace metric `mem_used_percent`
- [get_disk_usage](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/mcp_servers/monitoring/tools.py#160-223) → needs `CWAgent` namespace metric `disk_used_percent`

Without the CloudWatch Agent, these tools return:
```json
{"note": "No data — ensure CloudWatch Agent is installed and publishing mem_used_percent."}
```

**CPU metrics ([get_cpu_metrics](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/src/mcp_servers/monitoring/tools.py#21-76)) work without any agent** — AWS collects those automatically.

### Do You Need It Right Now?

**No — skip it for now.** The agent will still work with just CPU metrics.
Come back to this later when you want full observability.

### How to Install (when ready)

**Step 1:** SSH into your EC2 instance or use AWS Systems Manager Session Manager.

**Step 2:** Install the agent:
```bash
# Amazon Linux 2 / Amazon Linux 2023
sudo yum install -y amazon-cloudwatch-agent

# Ubuntu
sudo apt-get install -y amazon-cloudwatch-agent
```

**Step 3:** Create the config file at `/opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/etc/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.json`:
```json
{
    "metrics": {
        "metrics_collected": {
            "mem": {
                "measurement": ["mem_used_percent"],
                "metrics_collection_interval": 60
            },
            "disk": {
                "measurement": ["disk_used_percent"],
                "resources": ["/"],
                "metrics_collection_interval": 60
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Step 4:** Start it:
```bash
sudo /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/bin/amazon-cloudwatch-agent-ctl \
    -a fetch-config -m ec2 \
    -c file:/opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/etc/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.json \
    -s
```

**Step 5:** Wait 2 minutes, then verify in CloudWatch Console → Metrics → CWAgent namespace.

---

## ⚡ Part 5: EventBridge → Lambda — Why This Exists

### The Problem It Solves

This is the **trigger chain**:
```
CPU spikes on EC2 instance
        │
        ▼
CloudWatch alarm fires (it detects CPU > 80%)
        │
        ▼
CloudWatch changes alarm state from OK → ALARM
        │
        ▼
EventBridge catches that state change (it watches for alarm events)
        │
        ▼
EventBridge invokes your Lambda function
        │
        ▼
Lambda runs your Python code → Agent investigates → Notifies Teams
```

**Without EventBridge:** Nothing connects the alarm to your agent. The alarm fires, you get an email notification (if set up), and that's it. No automation.

**With EventBridge:** The alarm automatically wakes up your AI agent to investigate.

### The Bug That Was Fixed

[infra/app.py](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/infra/app.py) was missing one line. It created the EventBridge rule but never told it to call the Lambda:

```python
# BEFORE (broken — alarm fires but Lambda is never called):
agent_runner.add_dependency(monitoring)
app.synth()

# AFTER (fixed — alarm → EventBridge → Lambda):
agent_runner.add_dependency(monitoring)
monitoring.add_lambda_target(agent_runner.agent_fn)  # ← this line was missing
app.synth()
```

✅ **This is already fixed in your [infra/app.py](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/infra/app.py) now.**

---

## 🚀 Part 6: CDK vs Manual — How Deployment Works

### Do You Use CLI or Manual Console?

**You use CLI (CDK).** That's the whole point of having an [infra/](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/tests/integration/test_mcp_round_trip.py#25-48) folder.

Here's what CDK does automatically when you run `cdk deploy`:

| What CDK Creates | Console Equivalent |
|---|---|
| Lambda function with your code | Console → Lambda → Create function → upload ZIP |
| Lambda IAM role + all permissions | Console → IAM → Create role → attach 6 policies |
| CloudWatch Alarm | Console → CloudWatch → Create alarm |
| EventBridge Rule | Console → EventBridge → Create rule |
| VPC + subnets + security groups | Console → VPC → Create VPC wizard |
| CloudWatch Log group (2 week retention) | Console → CloudWatch → Log groups |

**CDK saves you ~1 hour of Console clicking every time you deploy.**

### How CDK Deployment Works Step by Step

```bash
# Step 1: Install CDK CLI (one time)
npm install -g aws-cdk

# Step 2: Bootstrap CDK in your account (one time per account/region)
cdk bootstrap aws://YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID/ap-southeast-2

# Step 3: Install CDK Python dependencies
pip install -e ".[infra]"

# Step 4: See what CDK will create (dry run, no changes)
cd infra
cdk synth

# Step 5: Deploy everything
cdk deploy --all --parameters DevOpsAgent-Monitoring:MonitoredInstanceId=i-YOUR_EC2_ID

# Or deploy one stack at a time:
cdk deploy DevOpsAgent-Networking
cdk deploy DevOpsAgent-Monitoring
cdk deploy DevOpsAgent-Runner
```

### The Missing Lambda Env Vars

The CDK stack currently only sets 3 env vars in the Lambda. You need to add your secrets too.

**Fix the CDK code** in [infra/stacks/agent_runner_stack.py](file:///c:/Users/pvhar/codelabs/devops-ai-agent/infra/stacks/agent_runner_stack.py), change lines 33–37:

```python
# CURRENT (missing important vars):
environment={
    "LOG_LEVEL": "INFO",
    "LOG_FORMAT": "json",
    "AWS_REGION_OVERRIDE": cdk.Aws.REGION,
}

# SHOULD BE:
environment={
    "LOG_LEVEL": "INFO",
    "LOG_FORMAT": "json",
    "AWS_REGION": cdk.Aws.REGION,
    "AGENT_ID": "KYZ4EKSMX5",
    "AGENT_ALIAS_ID": "LFVTIWMNFK",
    "BEDROCK_MODEL_ID": "anthropic.claude-3-sonnet-20240229-v1:0",
    # TEAMS_WEBHOOK_URL: add later
}
```

**Or after deployment**, go to:
```
AWS Console → Lambda → devops-ai-agent-handler
→ Configuration → Environment variables → Edit
→ Add each variable manually
```

